export const notes = "\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>1. Water Management Overview \u2014 Four National Taps</h2>\n  <p>Singapore secures its water supply through <strong>four diversified sources</strong> known as the <em>Four National Taps</em>, managed by <strong>PUB (Public Utilities Board)</strong>.</p>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Tap 1</h4>\n      <p>Local Catchment Water (Reservoirs)</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Tap 2</h4>\n      <p>Imported Water from Johor, Malaysia</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Tap 3</h4>\n      <p>NEWater (Recycled/Reclaimed Water)</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Tap 4</h4>\n      <p>Desalinated Water (from seawater)</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Current demand:</strong> ~430 million gallons per day (mgd)<br>\n    <strong>Projected demand by 2060:</strong> Nearly double (~860 mgd)<br>\n    <strong>2060 targets:</strong> NEWater 55% | Desalination 30% | Johor import reduced to 0%\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Why diversification?</strong> Singapore is a small, densely populated island with no large rivers, limited land for reservoirs, and no hinterland. Dependence on any single source is a national security risk.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> PUB is the national water agency that owns, operates and regulates all aspects of Singapore's water supply, including drinking water, used water, and stormwater drainage.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>2. 1st Tap \u2014 Local Catchment Water (Reservoirs)</h2>\n  <p>Singapore has <strong>17 reservoirs</strong> covering <strong>two-thirds (2/3) of the island's land area</strong> \u2014 one of the highest catchment area-to-land ratios in the world.</p>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Key reservoirs:</strong> MacRitchie, Upper Seletar, Bedok, Kranji, Jurong Lake, Marina (largest)<br>\n    <strong>Marina Reservoir:</strong> 10,000 ha catchment \u2014 created by the Marina Barrage (2008)\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"process-flow\">\n    <h4>Treatment Process</h4>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">1</span> Screening \u2014 removes large debris</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">2</span> Coagulation / Flocculation \u2014 chemicals clump fine particles together</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">3</span> Sedimentation \u2014 clumps (flocs) settle to the bottom</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">4</span> Filtration \u2014 water passes through sand/gravel filters</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">5</span> Chlorination \u2014 disinfects remaining pathogens</div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    Singapore uses an <strong>urbanised catchment</strong> \u2014 rain that falls on roads, parks, rooftops and buildings drains into canals and rivers, which flow into reservoirs. Even city streets contribute to water supply.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> The Marina Reservoir is special because it is located in the <em>heart of the city</em>. Its 10,000 ha catchment is about 1/6 of Singapore's total land area.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>3. 2nd Tap \u2014 Imported Water from Johor</h2>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>1962 Water Agreement:</strong> Singapore purchases water from Johor, Malaysia<br>\n    <strong>Price:</strong> 3 sen per 1,000 gallons (historically very cheap)<br>\n    <strong>Volume:</strong> Up to 250 million gallons per day (mgd)<br>\n    <strong>Expiry:</strong> August 2061\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Historical context:</strong> There were two water agreements \u2014 the 1927 Agreement (expired 2011) and the current <strong>1962 Agreement (expires 2061)</strong>. Water is drawn from the Johor River, treated at Johor Bahru, then piped across the Causeway. It is further treated at Kranji and Woodlands Waterworks in Singapore.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Political sensitivity:</strong> Water is a key issue in Singapore-Malaysia relations. Singapore's long-term goal is to be <em>completely self-sufficient</em> by 2061 so it does not need to renew the agreement. PUB plans to phase out imported water entirely by investing in NEWater and desalination.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> A key disadvantage of imported water is that it creates <em>political dependence</em> on another country. This is why Singapore is aggressively expanding NEWater and desalination capacity.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>4. 3rd Tap \u2014 NEWater (Recycled Water)</h2>\n  <p><strong>NEWater</strong> is highly purified reclaimed water produced from treated used water (sewage/wastewater). It meets WHO drinking water standards \u2014 and is often purer than tap water.</p>\n  <div class=\"process-flow\">\n    <h4>3-Step NEWater Process</h4>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">1</span> <strong>Microfiltration (MF)</strong> \u2014 Removes suspended solids, bacteria, and some protozoa using tiny membrane pores</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">2</span> <strong>Reverse Osmosis (RO)</strong> \u2014 High pressure pushes water through a semi-permeable membrane, removing dissolved salts, heavy metals, and viruses</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">3</span> <strong>Ultraviolet (UV) Disinfection</strong> \u2014 UV light kills any remaining microorganisms</div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>First plant:</strong> Opened 2003<br>\n    <strong>Number of plants:</strong> 5 NEWater plants<br>\n    <strong>Current supply:</strong> ~40% of Singapore's water demand<br>\n    <strong>2060 target:</strong> 55% of demand\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Uses of NEWater:</strong> Primarily supplied to <em>industries</em> (especially wafer fabrication/semiconductor plants) which require ultra-pure water. A small percentage is blended into reservoirs to replenish drinking water supply during dry weather.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> NEWater is <em>cheaper than desalination</em> but <em>more expensive than conventional reservoir treatment</em>. It is drought-resilient since it recycles water regardless of rainfall.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>5. 4th Tap \u2014 Desalination</h2>\n  <p><strong>Desalination</strong> converts seawater into freshwater by removing salt \u2014 making Singapore's supply truly weather-independent.</p>\n  <div class=\"process-flow\">\n    <h4>Desalination Process (Seawater Reverse Osmosis \u2014 SWRO)</h4>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">1</span> Pre-treatment \u2014 Screening and filtering to remove large particles from seawater</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">2</span> High-pressure Reverse Osmosis \u2014 Seawater forced through semi-permeable membranes; salt and impurities rejected</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">3</span> Post-treatment \u2014 Remineralisation (adding minerals back), pH adjustment, chlorination</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">4</span> Distribution \u2014 Freshwater distributed to the grid</div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>First plant:</strong> SingSpring Desalination Plant, Tuas \u2014 opened 2005<br>\n    <strong>Number of plants:</strong> 5 desalination plants<br>\n    <strong>Current capacity:</strong> ~25\u201330% of demand<br>\n    <strong>Key plants:</strong> Tuas, Tuas SWRO, Jurong Island SWRO, Marina East, Keppel Marina East\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Advantage</h4>\n      <p>Drought-proof \u2014 not dependent on rainfall; seawater is virtually unlimited</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Disadvantage</h4>\n      <p>Very energy-intensive \u2014 uses 3\u201310x more energy than conventional water treatment; contributes to carbon footprint</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> Both NEWater and desalination use Reverse Osmosis (RO). The key difference: NEWater treats <em>used water</em> (sewage), while desalination treats <em>seawater</em>.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>6. Marina Barrage</h2>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Cost:</strong> S$226 million<br>\n    <strong>Construction:</strong> 22 March 2005 \u2013 31 October 2008<br>\n    <strong>Location:</strong> Mouth of Marina Channel, central Singapore<br>\n    <strong>Catchment:</strong> 10,000 ha (about 1/6 of Singapore's land area)\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Function 1: Water Supply</h4>\n      <p>Creates Marina Reservoir \u2014 Singapore's 15th reservoir and largest, supplying freshwater from an urban catchment in the city centre</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Function 2: Flood Control</h4>\n      <p>Prevents flooding in low-lying areas of central Singapore (Chinatown, Boat Quay, Orchard Road area) by controlling water levels in Marina Bay</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <h4>How flood control works:</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>9 crest gates</strong> (each 70 m wide): Open during low tide to discharge excess rainwater into the sea by gravity</li>\n      <li><strong>7 large pumps</strong> (total capacity: 280 m\u00b3/s): Pump excess water out during high tide or heavy rain when gates cannot open by gravity</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>Before the barrage, Marina Bay was a tidal saltwater estuary and flooding in Orchard Road was common. After the barrage, the bay became a freshwater lake.</p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Bonus benefit:</strong> Marina Bay is now a vibrant urban waterfront \u2014 surrounded by Gardens by the Bay, Marina Bay Sands, and recreational spaces. The barrage itself has a rooftop green space and is a tourist attraction.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>7. Flood Management</h2>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Total investment:</strong> Over S$2 billion spent on flood management infrastructure<br>\n    <strong>Before improvements:</strong> ~3,200 ha of Singapore was flood-prone<br>\n    <strong>After improvements:</strong> Less than 30 ha flood-prone \u2014 a reduction of over 99%\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"process-flow\">\n    <h4>Key Flood Management Methods</h4>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">1</span> <strong>Canal widening and deepening</strong> \u2014 e.g. Bukit Timah Canal \u2014 increases water-carrying capacity</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">2</span> <strong>Detention tanks</strong> \u2014 Underground tanks (e.g. Stamford Diversion Canal, Alexandra Canal) temporarily store excess stormwater</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">3</span> <strong>Marina Barrage flood control</strong> \u2014 9 crest gates + 7 pumps protect central Singapore</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">4</span> <strong>Pumping stations</strong> \u2014 Pump floodwater away from low-lying areas</div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-num\">5</span> <strong>Real-time monitoring</strong> \u2014 Water level sensors and CCTV cameras across the island for early warning</div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Remaining challenge:</strong> Climate change is causing more intense and unpredictable rainfall events. Singapore continues to invest in drainage infrastructure to cope with flash floods.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> When asked to \"explain\" a tap or method, use this structure: <em>What it is \u2192 Process \u2192 Advantages \u2192 Disadvantages \u2192 Evaluation</em>. For \"evaluate\" questions, always consider sustainability, cost, energy use, and reliability.\n  </div>\n</div>\n";

